<p><strong>Sources</strong></p>
<p>
The specific website used to source manuals largely depends on the system and the community based around it. Manuals often exist on many different websites and in different forms.
</p>
<p>
In general, the following priorities are used when determining which source to use:
</p>
<ol>
  <li><b>Quality</b>: Higher quality &gt; lower quality</li>
  <li><b>Resolution</b>: Higher resolution &gt; lower resolution</li>
  <li><b>Color</b>: Color &gt; Black and White</li>
  <li><b>Watermark</b>: Non-watermarked manuals &gt; watermarked manuals</li>
  <li><b>Language</b>: Single language &gt; multi-language (unless it's just truncated)</li>
  <li><b>Archives</b>: Archive.org sources &gt; other sources</li>
  <li><b>Ownership</b>: Community-owned websites &gt; individually-owned websites</li>
</ol>
<p>
As you can see, there are a large number of considerations to keep in mind when identifying the appropriate source for each individual manual.
</p>

<p><strong>Source formats</strong></p>
<p>
The following source formats are currently supported when converting to PDF:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>pdf</li>
  <li>cbz / zip</li>
  <li>cb7 / 7z</li>
  <li>cbr / rar</li>
  <li>html</li>
  <li>txt</li>
  <li>doc / docx / wri / rtf</li>
  <li>jpg / jpeg / png / gif / bmp / tiff</li>
</ul>
<p>
Once downloaded, these formats will all be converted into PDF, maintaining the quality of the original manual when possible.
</p>

<p><strong>Archives</strong></p>
<p>There are 2 archives available for every system:</p>
<ul>
   <li><strong>original</strong> - The highest, original quality PDF format available based on the identified source</li>
   <li><strong>compressed</strong> - A highly-optimized, compressed version of the PDF based on a number of factors</li>
</ul>
<p>
  In general, the compressed format is meant to be readable on a resolution up to 1920x1440. The compression effectively:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>Resizes manuals to be no larger than 1920x1440</li>
   <li>Uses high JPEG compression for large resolutions</li>
   <li>Uses low JPEG compression for low resolutions</li>
   <li>Converts jpx/jbig2/uncompressed images to jpeg for rendering performance</li>
   <li>Converts ICC color profiles to RGB for rendering performance</li>
</ul>
<p>
Note that, for some manuals, the "compressed" file may be larger than the original.  This is due to the conversion of jpx/jbig2 images to jpeg images for the purposes of rendering performance.
</p>

